{"id":"1607.08867","submitter":"Arnout Boelens","authors":"Andrzej Latka, Arnout M. P. Boelens, Sidney R. Nagel, Juan J. de Pablo","title":"Drop splashing is independent of substrate wetting","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Physics of Fluids 30, 022105 (2018)","doi":"10.1063/1.5012529","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A liquid drop impacting a dry solid surface with sufficient kinetic energy\nwill splash, breaking apart into numerous secondary droplets. This phenomenon\nshows many similarities to forced wetting, including the entrainment of air at\nthe contact line. Because of these similarities and the fact that forced\nwetting has been shown to depend on the wetting properties of the surface,\nexisting theories predict splashing to depend on wetting properties as well.\nHowever, using high-speed interference imaging we observe that at high\ncapillary numbers wetting properties have no effect on splashing for various\nliquid-surface combinations. Additionally, by fully resolving the Navier-Stokes\nequations at length and time scales inaccessible to experiments, we find that\nthe shape and motion of the air-liquid interface at the contact line at the\nedge of the droplet are independent of wettability. We use these findings to\nevaluate existing theories and to compare splashing with forced wetting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 29 Jul 2016 16:41:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 24 Jan 2018 00:01:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-14"}
